\b\i\f1 8. Which of the below-mentioned protocol(s) is susceptible to sniffing? [Sniffing]\par
\b0\i0\f2\par
Sniffing is the practice of catching internet packets. This is done within the transport protocol and thus involves \ul TCP \ulnone & \ul UDP\ulnone  packets and \ul HTTP\ulnone  data segments. Sniffing is also called eavesdropping or wiretapping. It is performed by installing an application or hardware device to capture network packets (a sniffer). Using a sniffer, an attacker could capture email traffic (IMAP, SMTP), web traffic (HTTP), FTP (Telnet, SMB, NFS etc). A sniffer can display, watch and log traffic. \par
\par
Sniffing can be avoided by using safe, secure protocols such as HTTPS, Secure Socket Layers (SSH). If an insecure protocol must be used, all the data sent should be encrypted. If required, also a VPN can be used to secure access to users. \par
