\b\i\f2 17. Intrusion Detection System (IDS) & Intrusion Prevention System (IPS) [IDS & IPS]\par
\b0\i0\par
An IDS works proactively to detect an intrusion and is subset of the IPS. A IDS can be implemented either in a system, subsystem, network or subnetwork. All IDSs has a response function on specific triggers which often could perform an action like calling a human to decide what furhter actions that are needed. If an IDS goes into protection mode and tries to isolate an intrudor and constrain its access, it is also an Intrudion Prevention System (IPS). \par
\par
There 2 general types of Intrusion Detection Systems: \par
- The Signature-based (Identifies intrusion by patterns) \par
- The Anamoly-based (Identifies intrusion by hueristics)\par
\par
An IDS could also be host-based or network-based. \par
\par
An IDS can be placed either at the front of a monitored subnetwork or on the inside of a subnetwork. The one in front monitors all traffic as it enters the network. The other one (the internal), monitors traffic within the network. \par
\par
To not make an IDS vulnerable to a DoS-attack, it runs in stealth mode. This means that is is using 2 network interfaces, one to monitor the traffic and another to communication with e.g. an alarm. The IDS works like a perfect passive wiretap. \par
\par
An Intrusion Prevention System can be configured to take action to block an attack or reduce its impact by: continue to monitor the network, block the attack, redirecting the traffic to a monitored host, or terminating the session, reconfiguring the network to bringing other hosts online (adjusting load balancers), adjusting performance (dropping some of the incoming traffic), deny access to certain hosts, shut down parts of the network, shut down the entire network. \par
