\b\i\f1 18. Describe three reasons why penetrate-and-patch is a misguided strategy. [Program Security]\f2\fs48\par
\b0\i0\f1\fs32\par
Penentrate-and-patch is a misguided strategy since it dodges the principle of security by design. It is based on a reactive approach where we act upon a fault, bug or security breach instead of thinking of it in advanced. A more preferred way to work is to identify threats, balance the risks and invest in preventive approach. A good argument is that it is harder to detect an error inside a system, thus preventing the error to get inside is a better measure. Patching may also be more expensive and infected systems also tend to be staging areas for other malware. The main reason for that we should avoid penentrate & patching strategy is because the later a security flaw, bug or fault is found in a program or network, the more expensive it is to control it. The earlier it can be addressed in the information security development, the cheaper it is to address. Addressing security flaws during development instead of after a release is much cheaper. \par
